  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+Karl-Friston+information-theory] IMPLEMENTATION-READY — Active Inference Engine (Free Energy Minimization). Model each person as a generative model with prior beliefs, precision weights, and a prediction error signal. predict() computes: (1) expected_state = person.beliefs mapped to a prior distribution, (2) prediction_error = stimulus minus expectation, weighted by stimulus.personalRelevance * stimulus.intensity, (3) precision = 1 / (1 + person.traits.openness ?? 0.5) — lower openness = higher precision = stronger prior, (4) free_energy = precision * prediction_error^2, (5) emotion = sign(prediction_error) * free_energy → distress if violated, relief if confirmed, (6) behavior = if free_energy > threshold: active_inference (change environment) else perceptual_inference (update belief). Maps cleanly to: anxiety (high precision + prediction error), confirmation bias (high precision suppresses update), depression (learned helplessness = belief that actions can't reduce free energy), curiosity (low precision = exploration). Implement as ~60 lines of arithmetic in predict(). — Math: F = -log P(observation | beliefs) + KL[posterior || prior]; minimize by either updating beliefs (perception) or changing inputs (action); [psychology+dynamical-systems+opponent-process-theory+Richard-Solomon] Opponent Process Affective Dynamics. Emotions are not states but trajectories: every stimulus triggers a primary process (fast, fades quickly) and an opponent process (slow-building, outlasts the primary). The net felt emotion at time t is primary(t) - opponent(t). This explains: opponent process theory of addiction (pleasure → craving), post-traumatic relief (fear → calm), love as attachment (pleasure → pain-of-absence), emotional adaptation (hedonic treadmill). Encode as: primary_valence = stimulus.intensity * relevance * sign(match_to_need), opponent_valence = -0.7 * primary_valence (delayed, persists), net_emotion = primary + opponent. The ratio primary:opponent is modulated by person.traits.neuroticism. Distinct from free-energy: this is a temporal dynamics engine, not a belief-updating engine — they are composable. — Math: dA/dt = -A/τ_fast + stimulus; dB/dt = -B/τ_slow + k*A; emotion(t) = A(t) - B(t); [motivational-psychology+behavioral-economics+cognitive-bandwidth+Maslow-revised] Hierarchical Needs as a Deficit-Driven Priority Queue. Rather than Maslow's static pyramid, model needs as a dynamic priority queue where unmet needs commandeer cognitive resources proportional to their deficit magnitude and biological urgency weight. predict() computes: for each need in person.needs, deficit = urgency_weight[need] * (1 - satiation_level), dominant_need = argmax(deficit), behavior = action that most reduces dominant_need deficit in current context. Urgency weights: physiological > safety > belonging > esteem > self-actualization (fixed biological ordering). Satiation decays over time modeled by context. This explains threat-salience under hunger/fear, why mastery motivation disappears under poverty (cognitive bandwidth tax), why belonging needs spike in isolation. Composable with free-energy: the dominant need defines the generative model's prior. — Math: priority(need_i) = w_i * max(0, threshold_i - satiation_i); behavior = argmax_{a} sum_i priority(need_i) * utility(a, need_i)",
